<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-369-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 369 064  OV: 08 368 994.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 23 1990 v7 n16 p86(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Logitech Inc. ScanMan Plus. (Hardware Review) (one of eightevaluations of hand-held scanning systems in 'Hand-held scannersfit for certain tasks.') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Halliday, Caroline; Damore, Kelley.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Logitech Inc's $538 ScanMan Plus hand-held scanner is easy toalign but difficult to move straight because its rollers providelittle traction.andP;  It is bundled with a full-featured paint programand offers Catchword, an optical character recognition (OCR)program that employs omnifont technology.andP;  Catchword can examinethe shape of a character in order to identify fonts withouttraining but is relatively slow.andP;  It can quickly translate textsamples with acceptable accuracy.andP;  The OCR program is bundled witha text editor for correcting errors.andP;  The OCR processautomatically combines the two halves of a page after scanningboth.andP;  A disadvantage of Catchword's omnifont technology is thefact that users cannot add to the characters recognized, butresults are satisfactory with common fonts.andP;  Buyers of ScanMan arepleased with its price/performance ratio and stable shape.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Logitech Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Logitech ScanMan Plus (Scanning device).andO;Topic:     ScanningGraphics SystemsEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Logitech Inc.andM;SCANMAN PLUSandM;The Logitech scanner is easy to align, due to its angular shape.andP;  However,its two rear rollers are slick and do not provide enough traction, making itdifficult to scan straight.andP;  The ScanMan Plus is supplied with PaintShow Plussoftware, a full-featured paint program.andM;The scanner requires a device driver in CONFIG.SYS to operate.andP;  It has awell-recessed contrast knob.andM;Catchword is the only OCR program reviewed that makes use of imnifonttechnology.andP;  Omnifont technology examines the shape of a character, enablingthe OCR software to identify fonts without training.andP;  With its pull-down andsimple-to-use menus, Catchword's interface proved the best of the bunch.andM;Although translation was slow (because of the omnifont technology), Catchwordwas able to translate all the text samples with an adequate degree ofaccuracy and no font training.andP;  When run in interactive mode, in which theuser is promised for characters that Catchword cannot identify, the resultswere satisfactory.andM;A text editor is bundled with the program, allowing rapid correction oferrors.andP;  Both left and right sides of pages are scanned before the OCRprocess starts, and the two halves are automatically combined.andM;Besides being slow, a disadvantage of omnifont technology is that if acharacter is not understood, the user cannot add to the charactersrecognized.andP;  However, for common fonts, such as Courier, Helvetica and TimesRoman, the results are satisfactory.andM;Logitech Inc., of Fremont, Calif., can be reached at (415) 795-8500.andM;Buyers say ...andM;Ray Slogar, manager of information systems for Lesea Inc., a broadcastingcompany in South Bend, Ind., has been using Logitech's ScanMan Plus to inputsmall pieces of artwork.andP;  He does not use any OCR software.andM;The price/performance ratio is good, and installation was easy, he said.andM;Slogar did notice distortion with scanned images.andP;  &quot;It is not 100 percent[accurate], but I don't need it to be,&quot; he said.andP;  Slogar recommended usingthe scanner with a paint program.andM;Gary Freed, president of Computer Consultants Inc., a hardware and softwaretesting firm in Melrose Park, Pa., has tested many hand-held canners,including those from DFI and Nisca.andP;  He prefers Logitech's ScanMan Plus.andM;Freed particularly likes the ScanMan's design, which allows him to move thescanner with little difficulty.andP;  &quot;I like the shape of the head,&quot; he said.andO;&quot;It fits around the hand and gives more stability.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>